<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920129-0044</DOCNO><DOCID>920129-0044.</DOCID><HL>   ITT Finance Unit   Settles Allegations   On Bill Collection</HL><DATE>01/29/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7</SO><CO>   ITT</CO><MS>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>CONGLOMERATES (CGL)DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, CREDIT INSTITUTIONS (FIS)</IN><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)WISCONSIN (WI)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- ITT Corp.'s consumer financial services unitagreed to pay a total of $1.4 million to settle allegationsmade by the Wisconsin attorney general accusing the companyof illegal bill-collection practices.   ITT's Aetna Finance Co., which does business as ITTFinancial Services, agreed to the settlement following an18-month investigation by the attorney general's office. TheITT unit hasn't any connection with Hartford, Conn.-basedAetna Life andamp; Casualty Co.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman for the attorney general's office said theinvestigation found widespread violations of bill-collectionlaws, such as multiple calls to debtors and their families,abusive language during calls, and calls to employers andfamily members about the debtor's delinquent bills. Theattorney general's investigation stemmed from dozens ofcomplaints received by the Wisconsin banking commissionerabout the company.   The settlement was approved by a state court in Madison,Wis.   ITT neither admitted nor denied the allegations. Aspokeswoman for the company's consumer-financial servicesunit said the company cooperated with the investigation.&quot;We're concerned about every collection complaint,&quot; she said.   The $1.4 million settlement includes $110,000 to fund thehiring of an independent auditor, who will review and reporton the company's collection procedures for six to 12 months.The attorney general's office said it may take further actionif any alleged violations are found by the auditor.   The settlement also includes $25,000 to be used by thestate banking commissioner to educate consumers aboutdebt-collection laws.</TEXT></DOC>